\begin{abstract}
  We present DANA, a pure neural model for dynamic multi-depot vehicle routing
  with time windows (MDVRPTW) under spatial disaster conditions. DANA integrates
  three innovations from neural combinatorial optimization (NCO): a real-world
  road network encoder from RRNCO~\cite{rrnco2026}, dynamic context understanding
  from CCL~\cite{ccl2026}, and a multi-depot decoder based on
  RouteFinder~\cite{routefinder2024}, trained with POMO~\cite{pomo2020}
  reinforcement learning. Unlike prior work relying on synthetic Euclidean data,
  DANA operates on asymmetric distance and duration matrices from OpenStreetMap
  road networks. The model is trained with a humanitarian reward function
  derived from Chapter~14 of the VRP book~\cite{vrpbook}, optimizing response
  time, demand satisfaction, and equity. We evaluate DANA on six benchmarks
  following the Guidelines methodology~\cite{guidelines2021}, comparing against
  HGS~\cite{hgs2021}, LKH-3~\cite{neuralkh2021}, PyVRP, and OR-Tools with
  Wilcoxon signed-rank tests, Bonferroni correction, and PassMark time
  normalization.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Logistics distribution during spatial disasters---earthquakes, floods, or
epidemics---requires rapid, coordinated intervention where decisions must
account for highly dynamic parameters: roads close, new demands appear, and
depots become damaged or destroyed. This problem can be formulated as a dynamic
multi-depot vehicle routing problem with time windows (MDVRPTW), where new
constraints emerge in real time and solutions must prioritize humanitarian
objectives over commercial cost minimization.

Geographic Information Systems (GIS) are essential for capturing road network
topology and travel times under disaster conditions. However, existing neural
combinatorial optimization (NCO) methods are trained on simplified Euclidean
data~\cite{am2019,pomo2020} that does not reflect real-world routing
conditions. As demonstrated by FrontierCO~\cite{frontierco2026}, ML-based
solvers exhibit a catastrophic generalization gap---from 0.72\% on standard TSP
to 10--77\% on real-world instances---highlighting the urgent need for
GIS-aware training pipelines.

Recent advances address individual aspects of this challenge: RRNCO~\cite{rrnco2026}
introduces real-world routing datasets with OSM road network encoders;
CCL~\cite{ccl2026} handles dynamic constraint changes during route construction;
and RouteFinder~\cite{routefinder2024} provides a foundation model for
multi-depot VRPs. However, no existing work combines these capabilities with
humanitarian-specific objectives.

We propose DANA (Disaster-Aware Neural Algorithm), the first pure neural model
that jointly addresses: (1)~real-world road network asymmetry via OSM-derived
distance and duration matrices, (2)~dynamic disaster events (road closures,
demand surges, depot damage), (3)~multi-depot coordination with time windows,
and (4)~humanitarian reward optimization emphasizing response time, demand
satisfaction, and equity.

Our contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{DANA}: A pure neural architecture (no OR solvers, no ACO)
    combining RRNCO encoders, CCL context modules, and a RouteFinder-style
    multi-depot decoder for disaster-aware MDVRPTW.
  \item \textbf{Humanitarian reward formulation}: Operationalizes Chapter~14 of
    the VRP book for RL training, replacing commercial tour-cost minimization
    with response time, satisfaction, and equity objectives.
  \item \textbf{GIS-NCO bridge}: First integration of OSM road network data
    with dynamic disaster context in a learned solver.
  \item \textbf{Disaster benchmark}: Cairo and Nile Delta instances augmented
    with synthetic disaster events (road blockages, demand spikes, depot
    failures).
  \item \textbf{Rigorous evaluation}: Following the Guidelines
    methodology~\cite{guidelines2021}---HGS, LKH-3, PyVRP, and OR-Tools
    baselines; Wilcoxon signed-rank tests with Bonferroni correction; PassMark
    single-thread time normalization; performance and convergence charts.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Related Work}

\subsection{Neural Combinatorial Optimization}

NCO methods for routing problems have evolved from Pointer
Networks~\cite{ptrnets2015} and attention-based constructive
models~\cite{am2019} to reinforcement learning frameworks such as
POMO~\cite{pomo2020}. Bello et al.~\cite{ncorl2016} first applied RL to TSP,
while Nazari et al.~\cite{rlvrp2018} extended the approach to VRPs. Recent work
explores heavy decoder architectures~\cite{relight2025}, instance-conditioned
adaptation~\cite{glop2024}, and invariant representations~\cite{invit2024}.

However, FrontierCO~\cite{frontierco2026} demonstrates that ML solvers drop
from 0.72\% optimality gap on standard TSP to 10--77\% on real-world instances,
attributing the gap to four inadequacies: synthetic training data, Euclidean
distance assumptions, static constraints, and single-objective optimization.

\subsection{GIS-Aware Routing}

RRNCO~\cite{rrnco2026} introduced the first real-world NCO dataset using
OSM/OSRM road networks, providing asymmetric distance and duration matrices
across 100 cities. Their encoder architecture---comprising contextual gating,
neural adaptive bias (NAB), and adaptive attention fusion (AAFM)---processes
real-world road network features. RADAR~\cite{radar2026} further explores
asymmetry-aware distance representations for learned routing.

\subsection{Dynamic Constraints}

CCL~\cite{ccl2026} introduced step-wise context understanding through
Relational Graph Context Refiner (RGCR) and Temporal Step-wise Network Refiner
(TSNR) modules that handle dynamic constraint changes during route
construction. CARM~\cite{carm2026} rethinks constraint-aware state embeddings
for efficient neural routing.

\subsection{Humanitarian and Emergency Logistics}

Chapter~14 of the VRP book~\cite{vrpbook} establishes that disaster routing
requires fundamentally different objectives than commercial VRP: response time,
demand satisfaction, and equity take precedence over tour cost minimization.
The Disaster Survey~\cite{disaster2025} provides a comprehensive review of
relief distribution optimization. Recent work explores emergency logistics
planning~\cite{emergency2026} and dynamic emergency route optimization.

\subsection{Evaluation Methodology}

The Guidelines~\cite{guidelines2021} establish best practices for computational
testing of ML approaches to VRPs, emphasizing statistical tests (Wilcoxon
signed-rank), multiple comparison correction (Bonferroni), and hardware-aware
time normalization. The NCOSurvey~\cite{survey2024} provides a taxonomy of NCO
approaches and their evaluation gaps.

\section{Problem Formulation}

\subsection{MDVRPTW with Disaster Events}

We formulate the dynamic MDVRPTW as follows. Given a set of depots $D$, a set
of customers $C$, and a fleet of identical vehicles $V$, each vehicle starts at
a depot $d \in D$, visits a sequence of customers, and returns to its origin
depot. Each customer $i \in C$ has:

\begin{itemize}
  \item Demand $q_i$ (units of relief goods)
  \item Time window $[e_i, l_i]$ (earliest and latest service start)
  \item Service time $s_i$
  \item Location coordinates $(x_i, y_i)$ on the OSM road network
\end{itemize}

Travel between locations uses asymmetric distance $d_{ij}$ and duration
$t_{ij}$ derived from OSM road network routing via OSRM, not Euclidean
distance.

Disaster events modify the problem state during execution:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Road closure}: Edge $(i,j)$ becomes impassable ($d_{ij} = t_{ij} = \infty$)
  \item \textbf{Demand surge}: Customer demand increases $q_i \leftarrow q_i + \Delta q$
  \item \textbf{Depot damage}: Depot $d$ becomes unavailable; its vehicles and customers reassigned
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Humanitarian Objective}

Following Chapter~14 of the VRP book~\cite{vrpbook}, we define the
humanitarian reward function as a weighted combination:

\begin{equation}
R = \alpha R_{\text{response}} + \beta R_{\text{satisfaction}} + \gamma R_{\text{equity}} - \delta P_{\text{violation}}
\label{eq:reward}
\end{equation}

Where:

\begin{align}
R_{\text{response}} &= \mathbb{E}\left[e^{-t_i / T}\right] \quad \text{(exponential time penalty)} \\
R_{\text{satisfaction}} &= \frac{\sum_{i \in C} \text{served}_i}{\sum_{i \in C} q_i} \quad \text{(fraction of demand met)} \\
R_{\text{equity}} &= 1 - \text{Var}\left(\frac{\text{served}_i}{q_i}\right) \quad \text{(fairness across customers)} \\
P_{\text{violation}} &= \sum_{i \in C} \max(0, \text{arrival}_i - l_i) \quad \text{(time window violations)}
\end{align}

Here $t_i$ is the arrival time at customer $i$, $T$ is a temperature
parameter, and $\text{served}_i$ is the amount of demand satisfied at customer
$i$. The weights $\alpha, \beta, \gamma, \delta$ control the trade-off between
objectives. This formulation differs from classical VRP objectives that
minimize total tour length or number of vehicles; instead, it reflects the
humanitarian priority of getting relief to affected populations quickly and
fairly.

\section{DANA Architecture}

Figure~\ref{fig:architecture} illustrates the overall DANA architecture, which
consists of four components: an OSM-aware encoder, a dynamic context module, a
multi-depot decoder, and a humanitarian reward function.

