\section{Discussion}

\subsection{Key Findings}

\subsection{Limitations}

DANA faces several limitations. First, training on OSM data requires
pre-computed distance/duration matrices that may not reflect real-time traffic
conditions. Second, the model generalizes to the number of customers seen
during training and may not scale to significantly larger instances without
architectural modifications such as GLOP~\cite{glop2024} or
INViT~\cite{invit2024}. Third, disaster events in our benchmark are synthetic;
evaluation on real disaster data (e.g., historical earthquake or flood events)
remains future work.

\subsection{Future Work}

Several directions are promising: (1)~integrating real-time traffic data from
OSRM or Google Maps APIs for truly dynamic routing, (2)~multi-objective
preference optimization~\cite{preference2025} to allow human dispatchers to
specify trade-off preferences at inference time, (3)~extending the disaster
model to include cascading effects (e.g., aftershocks, flood propagation), and
(4)~deploying the trained policy in a real humanitarian logistics exercise with
NGO partners.

\section{Conclusion}

We presented DANA, a pure neural model for disaster-aware humanitarian
logistics routing. By combining OSM road network encoders, dynamic context
understanding, and a humanitarian reward function within a POMO training
framework, DANA addresses the critical gap between synthetic Euclidean NCO and
real-world disaster response requirements. Our evaluation across six
benchmarks, following the Guidelines methodology with appropriate statistical
tests, demonstrates that pure neural approaches can achieve competitive
performance on dynamic MDVRPTW with humanitarian objectives. All code and
trained models are publicly available at
\url{https://github.com/elfateh4/dana}.

